619976859.headline: Full Stack Software Engineer
619976859.summary: My name is Yasin Khan and I'm a software engineer based in the San Diego County. After graduating from the University of California, Santa Barbara with a degree in mathematics, I decided to test my luck in software development. I've always been drawn to coding because the thought of having an idea come to life that could benefit the world at the same time just seemed so appealing to me. So I started out how most people did, took a couple of udemy courses, enrolled in the Harvard CS50 class, and just learned through trial and error. After some time learning the core fundamentals, I enrolled in a coding boot-camp known as Hack Reactor. During my time there, I ate, slept, and breathed coding. By the end of my time there, I became a fully fledged, full-stack software engineer. However, the journey of a software engineer is never ending. There's always new tech stacks and languages to learn and ones that are constantly updating. For that reason, I'm constantly learning to this day and looking for new ways to improve myself. Do I think it gets taxing? Far from it. I love seeing the evolution of technology and using it to aid me in making my thoughts become a reality.

experience.description:
Led Hive's model serving team to ship two critical systems: the system to load models just-in-time in the inference path, and a fully rearchitected model autoscaler.

Drove the technical direction across the team - defined the roadmap, led design reviews, and established stronger software design patterns.

Cut paging by 4x by introducing more sophisticated model server health checks, improving load balancing strategies, and retargeting alerts to focus on externally visible symptoms rather than noisy internal signals.

experience.title: Teaching Assistant for CIS-110
experience.company_name: School of Engineering, University of Pennsylvania
experience.description:
Taught undergraduate students object-oriented programming, modularized code, data structure choice, documentation, and testing through a project-based Java class.

experience.title: Software Engineering Intern
experience.description: Designed and built a distributed, multi-threaded web-crawler written in Java. The crawler could simultaneously crawl over 100 domains (highest tested) while respecting a politeness delay between successive requests to the same domain. The crawler could also interleave tasks from multiple jobs, each with unique behavior specified in a JSON file.

experience.title: Batch Member
experience.description:
Participated in Hacker School - a self-directed, collaborative, project-based retreat for people who want to dedicate 3 months to becoming a better programmer.

My projects included: a JavaScript music sequencer web app that supports simultaneous editing by multiple clients, a digital synthesizer controlled by MacBook trackpad gestures built using ChucK, and a non-blocking Tic-Tac-Toe server that defeats clients using Min-Max.

experience.title: Research Assistant
experience.company_name: Center for Cognitive Neuroscience, University of Pennsylvania
experience.description:
Developed code in Python and Java to create counterbalanced stimulus sets as well as perform statistical analyses of brain image data.

Played active role in experimental design of fMRI studies examining the influence of high-level concepts on neural activation patterns in the early visual areas - a region of the brain previously thought to only encode low-level visual patterns.

Co-author of manuscript submitted to the Journal of Neuroscience, "Similarity of meaning modulates neural similarity within extrastriate cortex," describing the effects of meaning on neural representation in the visual areas, as well as the first direct, fMRI evidence of this phenomenon.

First author of research poster, Center for Undergraduate Research and Fellowships conference
Independently coordinated and administered fMRI scans to cohort of human subjects.

Received Undergraduate Research Mentorship Award, awarded to ~10% of over 500 applicants
